          <p>Another common use of <strong>mar</strong> is as a kind of subordinating conjunction expressing a concept similar to a manner adverb, i.e. modifying a verb and describing in more detail
              <em>how</em> the action denoted by that verb was carried out. When used as a conjunction, <strong>mar</strong> itself governs a verb rather than a noun, and asserts that the action
            denoted by the superordinate verb is similar in manner to the action denoted by the subordinate verb.</p>
          <p>In its first manner adverbal use, <strong>mar</strong> governs a (positive) relative clause, introduced by the relative particle <strong>a</strong>. The verb within the relative clause
            denotes an event which is assumed to have actually happened or which is going to actually happen. This usage corresponds to the English conjunction ‘as’. For example:</p>
